<graph id="s1_grd_cop_chain">
  <version>1.0</version>

  <!--
    Production SNAP graph for the Sentinel-1 adapter (TASK-014). Reproduces GEE
    COPERNICUS/S1_GRD preprocessing with the ESA Sentinel-1 Toolbox (the same
    engine GEE uses), emitting VV/VH sigma0 in dB PLUS the ellipsoid incidence
    angle, terrain-corrected onto EPSG:32611 at 10 m.

    Chain (matching the GEE S1_GRD recipe up to terrain correction):
      Read -> Apply-Orbit-File -> Subset (AOI n footprint, radar geometry)
        -> ThermalNoiseRemoval -> Remove-GRD-Border-Noise
        -> Calibration (sigma0, LINEAR) -> Terrain-Correction (SRTM 1Sec,
           EPSG:32611, + saveIncidenceAngleFromEllipsoid) -> Write (GeoTIFF-BigTIFF)

    The Subset to the AOI n granule-footprint (in radar geometry, after orbit so
    GCPs survive) is the adapter's "windowed read": terrain-correcting the full
    ~250 km IW swath at 10 m overflows SNAP's writer AND wastes compute. The
    footprint intersection (done in s1_snap.py) also avoids SNAP's "Empty region!"
    error on AOI areas this granule's swath does not cover.

    Output band ORDER (pinned; BigTIFF persists no band names): SNAP emits
    sigma0 VH first, then VV, then the angle band, i.e.
      band 1 = Sigma0_VH (linear), band 2 = Sigma0_VV (linear),
      band 3 = incidenceAngleFromEllipsoid (degrees).
    The S1Adapter maps by this fixed index order (descriptions are None under the
    BigTIFF writer) and asserts the angle domain at parity time.

    Key design notes (vs the throwaway TASK-005 spike graph):
      1. Terrain-Correction emits the ellipsoid incidence angle band
         (saveIncidenceAngleFromEllipsoid=true). The GEE S1_GRD `angle` band is the
         ellipsoid incidence (varies with range across the swath), NOT the local
         incidence angle (which swings with terrain).
      2. dB conversion is done in the ADAPTER (Python 10*log10), NOT in SNAP.
         LinearToFromdB scoped to the sigma0 bands DROPS the angle band from the
         output (it passes through only its named bands); converting all bands would
         log-scale the angle. Storing LINEAR sigma0 + angle keeps all 3 bands and
         the dB step (10*log10) is identical math, applied to VV/VH in s1.py.
      3. Write uses GeoTIFF-BigTIFF: the full-AOI-n-footprint output exceeds the
         classic GeoTIFF 4 GB cap; BigGeoTiffProductWriter handles it.

    Run via src/data/local_sources/s1_snap.py::build_s1_cache, or directly:
      <snap>/bin/gpt src/data/local_sources/s1_grd_graph.xml \
        -Pinput=<extracted .SAFE>/manifest.safe \
        -Pregion='POLYGON((lon lat, ...))' \
        -Poutput=<cache>/s1_grd_<granule>.tif
    (absolute gpt path; /usr/bin/snap is snapd, NOT ESA SNAP)
  -->

  <node id="Read">
    <operator>Read</operator>
    <sources/>
    <parameters class="com.bc.ceres.binding.dom.XppDomElement">
      <file>${input}</file>
    </parameters>
  </node>

  <node id="Apply-Orbit-File">
    <operator>Apply-Orbit-File</operator>
    <sources>
      <sourceProduct refid="Read"/>
    </sources>
    <parameters class="com.bc.ceres.binding.dom.XppDomElement">
      <orbitType>Sentinel Precise (Auto Download)</orbitType>
      <polyDegree>3</polyDegree>
      <!-- Don't fail the whole chain if the precise orbit isn't published yet;
           SNAP falls back to restituted. -->
      <continueOnFail>true</continueOnFail>
    </parameters>
  </node>

  <node id="Subset">
    <operator>Subset</operator>
    <sources>
      <sourceProduct refid="Apply-Orbit-File"/>
    </sources>
    <parameters class="com.bc.ceres.binding.dom.XppDomElement">
      <geoRegion>${region}</geoRegion>
      <copyMetadata>true</copyMetadata>
    </parameters>
  </node>

  <node id="ThermalNoiseRemoval">
    <operator>ThermalNoiseRemoval</operator>
    <sources>
      <sourceProduct refid="Subset"/>
    </sources>
    <parameters class="com.bc.ceres.binding.dom.XppDomElement">
      <selectedPolarisations>VV,VH</selectedPolarisations>
      <removeThermalNoise>true</removeThermalNoise>
    </parameters>
  </node>

  <node id="Remove-GRD-Border-Noise">
    <operator>Remove-GRD-Border-Noise</operator>
    <sources>
      <sourceProduct refid="ThermalNoiseRemoval"/>
    </sources>
    <parameters class="com.bc.ceres.binding.dom.XppDomElement">
      <selectedPolarisations>VV,VH</selectedPolarisations>
      <borderLimit>500</borderLimit>
      <trimThreshold>0.5</trimThreshold>
    </parameters>
  </node>

  <node id="Calibration">
    <operator>Calibration</operator>
    <sources>
      <sourceProduct refid="Remove-GRD-Border-Noise"/>
    </sources>
    <parameters class="com.bc.ceres.binding.dom.XppDomElement">
      <selectedPolarisations>VV,VH</selectedPolarisations>
      <outputSigmaBand>true</outputSigmaBand>
      <outputImageScaleInDb>false</outputImageScaleInDb>
    </parameters>
  </node>

  <node id="Terrain-Correction">
    <operator>Terrain-Correction</operator>
    <sources>
      <sourceProduct refid="Calibration"/>
    </sources>
    <parameters class="com.bc.ceres.binding.dom.XppDomElement">
      <demName>SRTM 1Sec HGT</demName>
      <demResamplingMethod>BILINEAR_INTERPOLATION</demResamplingMethod>
      <imgResamplingMethod>BILINEAR_INTERPOLATION</imgResamplingMethod>
      <pixelSpacingInMeter>10.0</pixelSpacingInMeter>
      <!-- EPSG:32611 (UTM 11N) to match the cube cell grid. -->
      <mapProjection>EPSG:32611</mapProjection>
      <nodataValueAtSea>false</nodataValueAtSea>
      <saveSelectedSourceBand>true</saveSelectedSourceBand>
      <!-- Emit the GEE `angle` band: ellipsoid incidence, NOT local incidence. -->
      <saveIncidenceAngleFromEllipsoid>true</saveIncidenceAngleFromEllipsoid>
    </parameters>
  </node>

  <!-- NO LinearToFromdB node: dB conversion (10*log10) is done in the adapter on
       VV/VH only (s1.py), so the angle band survives and stays in degrees. The
       cache stores LINEAR sigma0 + angle. -->

  <node id="Write">
    <operator>Write</operator>
    <sources>
      <sourceProduct refid="Terrain-Correction"/>
    </sources>
    <parameters class="com.bc.ceres.binding.dom.XppDomElement">
      <file>${output}</file>
      <formatName>GeoTIFF-BigTIFF</formatName>
    </parameters>
  </node>
</graph>
